Polls seem close and I have no special insights beyond that
Odinga is Kenyatta's preferred candidate and if corruption is as it seems, then there is a greater chance that there may not be a fair count of votes on election day.

I would put a naive base rate of 58% chance that the establishment choice wins the race given my own bias to see American politics reflected + Kenya's political history. Reliable governance would also probably gain a slight boost considering relative uncertainty in the world.
Odinga is up in polls
Kenya media reporting some backing from the Moi family may help him.

There seems to be an even growing divide between Odinga and Ruto. Now that their running mates have been announced, the general Kenyan population seems to favor Odinga and Martha Karua. Across many different polls, the tides have been slowing turning toward Odinga sitting at 42% vs 38% for Ruto according to Infotrak. Further, Kenyan Newspapers Review, Tuko, as of June 13, has Odinga Still Ahead of William Ruto Less Than 2 Months to Election Read more. On top of that, Kenyans newspaper stated, “Blinken affirmed the US will be keeping an eye on the election, recalling a conversation he had with Foreign Affairs Cabinet Secretary, Ambassador Raychelle Omamo. In addition, the US Secretary called on IEBC and the candidates - Deputy President William Ruto, former Prime Minister Raila Odinga, George Luchiri Wajackoya and David Mwaure to run peaceful campaigns.” This focus of the U.S. gives hope and light to Odinga who is running on a platform of democracy and free elections. I now have Odinga at 70% and Ruto at 30%.

While some may think that Odinga's choice to run a woman on his ticket appears weak, keep in mind that he already has household name recognition from his history in politics as PM. Also, it's his name that headlines the ticket, not his name as VP. I think voters yearn for familiar leaders with gravitas but also want someone representing ideas of modernity. This combo might just be it.

Recently news dropped that only 4 candidates are allowed to run for president in Kenya, including Odinga and Ruto. The other two candidates do not seem to have a clear shot to victory. Given the language articles are using to describe the election, I've revised my prediction up to 65% in favor of Odinga and the tightening of options for Kenyan voters.
Tracking closer towards the polls

With a 50% probability, Raila Odinga will win the next Kenyan Presidential election, 40% William Ruto will win and 10% someone else will become President. I am 50% sure that Odinga will win given that an independent Kenyan polling company listed Odinga as favored by 39% of voters, while Ruto is favored by 35% of voters. However, 14% of respondents said they are undecided and another 9% refused to disclose their preference according to the organization. Given that there is still a large portion of Kenyans that are still undecided, there is a very real possibility that the election can go either way. Furthermore, Odinga has also selected a Woman from the largest ethnic group in hopes of attracting more votes from the majority as well as encouraging more women to vote. However, given Kenya's patriarchal society structure this choice has the potential to be Odinga's downfall, as gender-based discrimination is still very prominent in the country.
Running mate selections might do a little but neither seems a huge advantage. This still feels largely like a toss up with Odinga having a slight lead due to backing from Kenyatta.
Odinga has backing of the leaders of the Kikuyu which will probably be the deciding ethnic group for the election.
- https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-05-18/opposition-leader-is-now-favorite-to-win-kenya-presidential-vote
EIU is slightly in favor of Odinga. https://www.eiu.com/n/competition-intensifies-ahead-of-kenyas-election/
Considering major concerns of the Kenyan people, chiefly being corruption, it may be that the civil population votes for the opposition candidate.

Odinga has been gunning for the presidency for 5 different terms. each time gaining more and more popularity. And now with the revamp of the election process, his ability to form a new party coalition stands in his favor. However, he has been neck and neck with his opponent Ruto who is the deputy but estranged from the current leader. The people are frustrated with him on top of the no apparent backing from the current president.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2022_Kenyan_general_election#President

Recent polls have Ruto leading by a substantial margin. Plus he has received favorable press due in part to his US visit in March. A broader trend of anti-establishment candidates has been on display globally, and Odinga represents the old guard. Polling, however, is unreliable in Kenya and some polls do show Odinga leading. Patronage networks also will work on Odinga’s favor.

Slightly reducing Ruto's odds in favour of a true outsider candidate owing to unstable geopolitical environment. Crashing Chinese economy likely to damage Chinese investment in Kenya, and war in Ukraine likely to push up food and fuel prices. These factors favour outsider candidates.

Updating based on: a) Risk of potential election rigging - increase Odinga's chances of winning https://theconversation.com/fears-of-election-rigging-may-fuel-further-abuses-in-kenya-democracy-could-be-the-loser-176113; however, may not impact probabilities significantly if both candidates engage in this b) On the other hand, @DomHajduk 's point on people trusting change more from Ruto as a new candidate is a good one which increases Ruto's chances On balance, reducing chance of someone else (would need new candidate to emerge plus gain enough support in short time period to win), and allocating extra to Ruto; downgrading Odinga slightly for almost 50/50 at this point

Dropping my vote on Other due to a long history of these two candidates being country leaders or on the ballot. I no longer thing either of them will drop out but am leaving 5% chances of one of them being forced to. Maintaining a very slight edge on Odinga

From what I gather, the two candidates are overwhelmingly overlapping on policy - of course with the sole exception of the BBI bill, though that may prove to be plenty. The BBI and Kenyattas move away from Ruto to support Odinga in some ways casts the election as a referendum on entrenching the current elites hold on power (Odinga, supported by Kenyatta), or opting for a prospect of more dynamism and hope for less unequal distribution on ethnic lines (Ruto).

Odinga took the initiative making Ruto's problematic history of corruption a lead issue and putting Ruto is on defensive saying Odinga is corrupt too. Mebbe to little too late. Ruto is a bit of an old boy, which could invite middlemen for international extractive industries to spread around what the Germans call "schmiergeld."

Odinga seems to be polling better but has lost four previous elections, I'm giving him the slight edge. Ruto, the current Deputy President has a decent chance if folks remain relatively happy with how things are - but could lose if voters lean towards wanting change. Still a decent chance someone else emerges before August or one of these candidates drops out and a close replacement fills in.

Seems very uncertain but Odinga more likely. From initial research it appears almost 50/50 with Odinga slightly ahead; slight chance it could be someone else due to general risk of Odinga or Ruto pulling out before August 2022 or someone else running and being successful. ______________________________________________________________________
